Date: Tue 30 Jun 2015
Source: CBC (Canada) TV News [edited]
http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/sudbury/sudbury-health-unit-receiving-increased-calls-about-hand-foot-and-mouth-disease-1.3132571


Yellowknife toddlers are catching hand, foot and mouth virus.

A disease that can cause a painful rash, sores and dehydration is circulating in Sudbury, the health unit says. Hand, foot and mouth disease is not on the Ontario Reportable Disease list, so there's no way to know how many cases are in Sudbury, said Lisa Schell, the manager of clinical and family services with the health unit. Schell said the health unit has been receiving calls from concerned parents.

"We do know that there are some children who have been diagnosed in our community," she said. Once we know that there are children in the community with hand, foot and mouth disease, there's certainly probably others who are ill with it as well."

Hand, foot and mouth disease is a virus-transmitted disease. Symptoms include a fever, poor appetite, lack of energy, discomfort, sore throat, headache, small painful mouth sores and a skin rash that looks like red spots, often with blisters on top. That rash usually appears on the palms of the hands and soles of the feet, but can show up on other areas of the body, Schell said.

There is no specific treatment. There is no blood test to confirm [the diagnosis], but Schell suggested a visit to a health care provider if a child is showing symptoms. "The diagnosis of hand, foot and mouth disease is based on the appearance of the rash," she said. "With hand, foot and mouth disease, we basically have to let it run its course. There's no specific treatment for the illness."

Children do not need to be excluded [from school] if they are diagnosed with hand, foot and mouth disease, Schell said. "If the child is unwell, let them lay low and treat them with bed rest and lots of fluids," she said. "Watch for signs of dehydration in case the child is not drinking or eating."

Serious complication includes dehydration, and Schell notes if a child with hand, foot and mouth disease has sores in their mouth, watch what they drink. "It can be painful, especially if they're drinking highly acidic fruit juices," she said. "The good thing about hand, foot and mouth is that once a child has had the disease, they are immune to it subsequently," she said.

The virus also tends to be more common in the summer and fall, Schell said. "It's just the nature of the virus," she explained. "We usually see more individuals getting out and about."

