[This is a rather inadequate account of an outbreak of hand, foot and mouth disease (HFMD) in Canada. Although comparatively uncommon in well-developed societies, hand, foot and mouth disease is common in underdeveloped or overpopulated regions of the world, and several different enteroviruses have been identified as responsible for outbreaks of hand, foot, and mouth disease, the most prevalent being several coxsackieviruses and, in particular, enterovirus 71, sometimes responsible for neurological effects.

Hand, foot and mouth disease usually begins with a low-grade fever and general fatigue. A rash of tiny, painful red spots will appear within a couple of days and will soon begin to blister and sometimes form ulcers. These spots may appear at several sites over the body. Lymph nodes in the neck may also become swollen. The virus can cause the throat to feel sore and painful. Rarely, dehydration may occur as the pain due to the blisters in the mouth can make drinking difficult.

Daycare centres, parks, nursery schools, and other places where children play with each other are potential sites for the infection to be transmitted among children. HFMD is most common in the summer and early fall.

High standards of personal and social hygiene are the best protection against hand, foot, and mouth disease.

The WHO Surveillance Summary includes information from countries where transmission of HFMD occurs and case counts are routinely reported. - Mod.CP

